{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\nSingle-stage NMOS common-source amplifier with a resistive drain load. The NMOS source and bulk are tied to ground, gate is driven by `Vin`, and drain is the output node `Vout`. A resistor `R` connects from `VDD` to `Vout`, converting NMOS drain-current variation into output voltage variation.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n- `VDD` supply: independent DC voltage source from node `VDD` to ground, value `5 V`.\n- Input source: independent voltage source driving `Vin`, with DC bias around `1.2 V` and AC magnitude `1` for gain analysis.\n- NMOS transistor:\n  - Model name: `NMOS`\n  - Drain: `Vout`\n  - Gate: `Vin`\n  - Source: ground\n  - Bulk: ground\n  - Dimensions: `W=50u`, `L=1u`\n- Load resistor `R`: from `VDD` to `Vout`, nominal `50k`, allowed range `10k` to `100k`.\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\nUse ground as the source, bulk, and global reference. Bias `Vin` near `1.2 V`, giving expected overdrive of about `0.5 V` assuming `Vth=0.7 V`. Choose `R=50k` initially, then verify `.op` keeps `Vout` above roughly `Vin - Vth`, preferably above `0.5 V`, so the NMOS remains in saturation.\n\n**Signal or Feedback Path**\nSmall-signal input is applied at `Vin` to the NMOS gate. Increasing `Vin` increases drain current, increasing the voltage drop across `R`, so `Vout` decreases. Expected gain is inverting. There is no intentional feedback path; only intrinsic MOS capacitances and output resistance contribute parasitic feedback/finite bandwidth behavior.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n- Final file must be named `p1.cir`.\n- Preserve node names exactly: `Vin`, `Vout`.\n- `Vin` must be driven by an explicit independent voltage source, not left as a bare node.\n- `Vout` must be the NMOS drain and amplifier output.\n- Include `.op`.\n- Include `.ac dec 20 1 1e9`.\n- Define model `NMOS` explicitly with `Vth=0.7 V` and `kp=100u`.\n- MOSFET instance must use `W=50u` and `L=1u`.\n- Use `R` between `VDD` and `Vout`, nominally `50k`.\n\n**Failure Risks to Avoid**\n- Do not swap drain/source such that `Vout` is not the drain.\n- Do not leave NMOS bulk floating; tie it to ground.\n- Do not omit the explicit `Vin` voltage source or its AC magnitude.\n- Do not bias `Vin` below `1.2 V`.\n- Do not choose `R` so large that `Vout` collapses near ground and forces triode operation.\n- Do not rename required nodes to lowercase or aliases such as `vin`, `out`, or `vout`.\n- Do not write a PMOS load or current-source load; the requested load is resistive `R`."}}
